<exercisegroup><introduction>
<assemblage><title>Division Algorithm for Polynomials</title><idx>division algorithm for polynomials</idx><p>If <m>f(x) </m> and <m>g(x)</m> are nonconstant polynomials with real coefficients, then there exist unique polynomials <m>q(x)</m> and <m>r (x)</m> such that
<me>f (x) = g(x)q(x) + r(x),</me>
where <m>\text{deg } r(x) \lt \text{deg }g(x)</m>.</p></assemblage>


<p>In Problems 57<ndash/>60, use polynomial division to divide <m>f(x) </m> by <m>g(x) </m>, and hence find the quotient, <m>q(x) </m>, and remainder, <m>r(x) </m>. (See Algebra Skills Refresher <xref ref="appendix-Polynomials-and-Factoring" text="type-hybrid"/> to review polynomial division.)</p></introduction>

