<exercise number="61"><statement><p>The remainder theorem states, If <m>P(x)</m> is a polynomial and <m>a</m> is any real number, there is a unique polynomial <m>Q(x)</m> such that
<me>P(x) = (x - a)Q(x) + P(a)</me>
Follow the steps below to prove the remainder theorem.
<ol>
    <li><p>State the division algorithm applied to the polynomials <m>P(x)</m> and <m>x-a</m>.</p></li>
    <li><p>What must be the degree of <m>r(x) </m> in this case?</p></li>
    <li><p>Evaluate your expression from part (a) at <m>x = a</m>. What does this tell you about the remainder, <m>r (x)</m>?</p></li>
</ol></p></statement>
<answer><p><ol>
    <li><p>If <m>P(x)</m> is a nonconstant polynomial with real coefficients and <m>a</m> is any real number, then there exist unique polynomials <m>q(x)</m> and <m>r (x)</m> such that
    <me>P(x) = (x - a)q(x) + r (x)</me> where <m>\text{deg }r (x)\lt \text{deg }(x - a)</m>.</p></li>
    <li><p>Zero</p></li>
    <li><p><m>P(a) = (a - a)q(a) + r (a) = r (a)</m>. Because <m>\text{deg }r(x) = 0 </m>, <m>r(x) </m> is a constant. That constant value is <m>P(a) </m>, so <m>P(x) = (x - a)q(x) + P(a)</m>.</p></li>
</ol></p></answer>
</exercise>

